00:00.940 --> 00:13.880
Okay, George, the tapes are rolling. Mm-hmm. Okay, you decided to be a writer at
an early age. Why did you choose science fiction? It seemed to me that science

00:13.880 --> 00:27.340
fiction always seemed the natural kind of writing. I grew up reading science
fiction, and its materials and the kinds of possibilities that it opened up to

00:27.340 --> 00:41.820
myself as a reader seemed to belong peculiarly to this time, as opposed to the
feeling I got when I read Charles Dickens or the 19th century writers, aside

00:41.820 --> 00:51.640
from Wells, of course, who straddled both centuries. It seemed to belong
uniquely to the 20th century. Of course, I didn't think about it that way. That

00:51.640 --> 01:01.300
came much later, but I think the instinctive reaction was that it was something
that was for me, and that it belonged to my time.

01:05.020 --> 01:13.780
When you were young, you were fairly active in fandom, and you had a magazine
called Epilogue. Can you tell us a little bit about that? Well, it ran for three

01:13.780 --> 01:26.420
issues. It started out as a publication called Viewpoint, and then the next two
issues were called Epilogue Viewpoint. They were fairly elaborately produced

01:26.420 --> 01:42.120
magazines for their time, photo offset with as much typesetting fakery as you
could bring about in a paste-up job. I think they can be seen in Sam Moskowitz's

01:42.120 --> 01:55.580
collection. Now, I don't even own the first two issues anymore. People like
Lester Del Rey, Judith Merrill, Michael Moorcock were published in the magazine.

01:56.440 --> 02:08.940
We were very militant about the future possibilities of a more literate science
fiction. We were down on Burroughs and Edward E. Smith and people of that kind,

02:09.500 --> 02:17.880
perhaps unfairly at the time. But we were very militant about things.

02:19.280 --> 02:32.980
I guess you might say that we were the American arm of the British New Wave,
since they seemed to find those of the British New Wave who wrote in to us,

02:33.160 --> 02:44.020
found kindred souls among us. Mike Moorcock especially, who said it was just
about the best American fanzine that he had ever read, that it set a high

02:44.020 --> 02:57.640
standard for discussion. Even somebody like Tom Boardman, the fan, no, John
Boardman, I'm sorry, the American fan, said that here is a fanzine that sets a

02:57.640 --> 03:04.280
standard higher than just about any other fanzine at the time. This was 1962-63.

03:06.080 --> 03:18.500
Other people who discovered it said that it was a science fiction and fantasy
fanzine, not a fandom fanzine. There were maybe 200 copies of each one

03:18.500 --> 03:24.200
circulated. I was quite proud of it at the time, but when I came to college, I'm
afraid it just went by the wayside.

