15:38.900 --> 15:47.920
In the past you've been critical of science fiction as a field where writers can
take the easy way out. Instead of coming up with something original they just

15:47.920 --> 15:59.520
follow a formula and seem to be doing okay. Is this trend continuing? Getting
worse? Getting better? What? Well, if you consider that science fiction has been

15:59.520 --> 16:13.240
anywhere between 10 and 15 percent of all fiction published, a great number of,
a great amount of it is derivative, built on pre-digested ideas and pre-digested

16:13.240 --> 16:27.900
plots. A good example takes to the concept of space colonies or the L-5 society
type of thing. It's very often simply been used as just another place to have an

16:27.900 --> 16:43.100
adventure of some kind or a place to set a murder mystery or a suspense story of
some kind or another. Predigestion seems to be the operative method of the

16:43.100 --> 16:55.100
copiers. Something comes in and it's slightly new and it's not used for itself.
It's used as just another place to have another barbaric adventure or whatever.

16:56.000 --> 17:09.400
It's easier to do this than to be original in each and every case. I'm afraid
that like many other writers I wrote what I was most influenced by. But as you

17:09.400 --> 17:20.600
go on you realize that quite possibly there is a way of doing things that is a
little more original than that. Do writers get to the point where they have a

17:20.600 --> 17:32.000
choice of following recipes and guaranteeing money or deciding to try something
new and risking the fact that maybe this isn't going to work out? Well the fact

17:32.000 --> 17:42.200
is that most science fiction has sort of built in sales potential. A science
fiction book will sell anywhere between 30 or 50,000 copies no matter who wrote

17:42.200 --> 17:53.920
it. This is unfortunate. Most of the best writers of science fiction however
become their own genres. Clark, Asimov, Heinlein are genres unto themselves

17:53.920 --> 18:07.680
within the genre and people will buy the name no matter what they write. This is
also unfortunate but it is a sign of some progress on the part of the writer. I

18:07.680 --> 18:15.820
think even if you write a fairly experimental kind of book like Macro Life
because of the built in potential there will be a certain number of readers who

18:15.820 --> 18:24.500
will buy it. There will be a smaller number of people who actually buy it
because they're interested in that kind of thing. Maybe their tastes will be

18:24.500 --> 18:39.460
widened by it. You really can't tell. You just have to do what you really want
to do. You can't simply write to fill a niche in the market. That's what strikes

18:39.460 --> 18:48.640
me as being very cynical in many writers. They do aim for a particular audience
and they aim to deliver a certain product and they don't seem to have any other

18:48.640 --> 19:01.380
ambitions. This would be fine if some of these writers were not capable of more,
in which case they're betraying their own abilities. This kind of comment on my

19:01.380 --> 19:13.120
part sounds perhaps very noble to many other writers and very idealistic and
they sort of shake their heads in the way that Claggett shook his head at Billy

19:13.120 --> 19:14.060
Budd's innocence.

19:16.840 --> 19:26.440
But that kind of attitude comes out of the environment in which they move. And I
think you can create for yourself an ambitious environment in which you will

19:26.440 --> 19:37.400
produce or at least have a shot at producing something that will be closer to
what you're capable of doing. Let's bring up the topic of critics in science

19:37.400 --> 19:46.800
fiction. There don't seem to be a lot of good ones, if there ever were. What do
you think as an author that critics should look for when they're reviewing a

19:46.800 --> 19:58.340
work? Well, they should primarily, if I were to give any advice to would-be
critics, is not to try to rewrite the book for the author and to hoist the

19:58.340 --> 20:07.780
author by his own petard and not that of the critic. Most critics, I'm afraid,
are self-appointed. It's very easy to simply appoint yourself a reviewer or a

20:07.780 --> 20:19.580
critic and start publishing criticism and then you acquire a few credits and you
do more. It's something that I don't believe that young writers should do at

20:19.580 --> 20:33.080
all. I did a lot of criticism when I was just beginning and I don't think I
acquitted myself very honorably at all. You tend to overpraise on the one hand

20:33.080 --> 20:47.420
and you tend to ignore things that you don't like. Criticism is something that
should be a very small part of any literature. There are some good critics, but

20:47.420 --> 21:01.640
that's a career in itself. Ultimately, a good critic is a person who writes a
kind of literature. An Edmund Wilson or a Lionel Trilling or people

21:01.640 --> 21:12.680
of that caliber are very rare. Science fiction has no good critics. After Damon
Knight, James Blish gave up. Alfred Bester was literally hounded out of

21:12.680 --> 21:23.900
reviewing because he was so hard on everything. The people who criticize now are
people simply looking to make a name for themselves by writing reviews of better

21:23.900 --> 21:24.740
writers' works.

21:28.740 --> 21:41.920
In your background, you were a fan, a writer, a critic. Now let's talk a little
bit about being an editor. How did you get involved in editing? Is that

21:41.920 --> 21:54.000
practiced at the expense of maybe not doing as much writing yourself? I think
most good writers edit because they wish to influence the field. They're curious

21:54.000 --> 22:09.200
to see what they can elicit from other writers. I'm talking primarily about
original anthologies or original magazines which publish new stories. You do it

22:09.200 --> 22:19.720
because you have an idea of how it should be done. As John Campbell once said,
when I edit, I am a hundred different writers. He would make suggestions to many

22:19.720 --> 22:32.020
of his writers and they would follow through. Many of the novels of Heinlein and
Vazimov and others were originally suggestions made by John Campbell. Then each

22:32.020 --> 22:41.480
of these writers, of course, carries out the idea in a very different way.
That's what Campbell meant by saying that I'm a hundred different writers when I

22:41.480 --> 22:53.900
edit and I'm only one writer when I write. But that's perhaps a little too easy.
I want to edit when I do and I want to do it all the time to influence how

22:53.900 --> 23:07.140
science fiction is written and to help produce the kinds of works that will set
a different example. And so far, I've had only limited opportunities to do this.

23:07.300 --> 23:11.040
I've edited five anthologies, some of them original, some of them not.

23:14.460 --> 23:25.700
I think they reflect the kind of science fiction that I would like to see
written. Although, if I really hold to the standard, I would have to say that

23:25.700 --> 23:37.920
however well these books have done, they are failures according to my outlook.
Ultimately, you have to accept as an editor the best that you can get and that

23:37.920 --> 23:41.500
may not reach the level that you desire.

