25:04.680 --> 25:13.360
these two books write beautifully, but they don't think very much. And he said
the great problem of science fiction is you have people who write beautifully

25:13.360 --> 25:22.680
and don't think, and you have people who think gorgeously and can't write. And
this impressed me because I've always believed that the secret to writing

25:22.680 --> 25:34.300
science fiction was to combine a whole set of virtues in one writer. And this
seems to be a very difficult thing to do. However, I do believe that these

25:34.300 --> 25:48.700
various virtues that go to make good science fiction, thinking and writing well,
for example, can be developed in intelligent writers in the same way that people

25:48.700 --> 25:58.020
develop the strength of various fingers when they practice the piano. But they
don't start early. They don't do it consciously. They don't really try. They

25:58.020 --> 26:04.440
settle for what actually sells, and it gets published, and then they don't work
beyond that point.

26:07.420 --> 26:22.820
I was very impressed with Campbell, and he valued disagreement above easy
agreement. He told me, if you agree with me, I'll change my mind. Great teacher

26:22.820 --> 26:33.760
in one respect. He still has quite an influence on the field, which I know some
people don't consider all that in that much of a positive fashion. Do you think

26:33.760 --> 26:44.260
that his influence was positive overall? I think it was positive, and I think
his disciples do not make the best case for him. They do not represent his

26:44.260 --> 26:59.400
ideas, and I think that it's the worst of John Campbell's effect on writers and
on the publishing of science fiction that has come in for deserved attack. The

26:59.400 --> 27:11.140
kind of interpretation of Campbell that makes sense out of Campbell's approach.
I think Greg Benford put it, Campbell basically wanted broader horizons and a

27:11.140 --> 27:23.660
deeper sense of humanity in his writers. And that's the kind of defense that is
not made of John W. Campbell. I think that John Campbell's legitimate heirs are

27:23.660 --> 27:37.400
people like Ursula Le Guin, Gregory Benford, perhaps Arthur C. Clarke, Philip K.
Dick, Gene Wolfe, writers who bring a sense of human character into an area of

27:37.400 --> 27:51.440
broader horizons in ideas, in considering the future of science and technology,
in considering many of the softer sciences. I think the people who defend

27:51.440 --> 28:02.320
Campbell along the lines of, you know, let's have more hard science and
engineering in our fiction don't really understand what he was trying to do. I

28:02.320 --> 28:14.420
think it was James Blish who said that when you say hard science fiction, what
he meant by it is hard science fiction across the board. Hard thinking, fine

28:14.420 --> 28:26.660
writing, hard characterization, that unity of values that I alluded to before.
That's what Campbell really pointed to. And of course, he failed to bring about

28:28.800 --> 28:41.640
this kind of science fiction, although he had some success. Anybody would have
to fail to some degree. But I think the people who defend Campbell are usually

28:41.640 --> 28:46.920
those who turn off the literary or ambitious writer.

28:50.980 --> 29:00.920
Now let's change topics and discuss your individual works. Our first exposure to
you in novel form was The Omega Point, which we now know is the middle of a

29:00.920 --> 29:14.980
trilogy. What was it intended to be when you first wrote it? Well, I originally
intended it to be a colorful, Eisensteinian space opera. Anyone who's seen the

29:14.980 --> 29:23.680
film with Sergei Eisenstein, like Alexander Nevsky or Ivan the Terrible, would
see what I mean by that. A colorful, intense,

29:26.540 --> 29:38.880
filled with characters who are always on edge. I simply wanted to carry out a
certain kind of aesthetic wish, and I'm afraid that I fell into a certain kind

29:38.880 --> 29:55.620
of science fiction. The book has been called a metaphysical space opera by Peter
Nichols, a science fiction encyclopedia, and it is that. And I don't think that

29:55.620 --> 30:09.700
it's a departure for me in any way. I think it was what I could do at the time.
There is a fair amount of my background in the story, I suppose. If I wanted to

30:09.700 --> 30:20.820
be psychoanalytic, I came out of a ruined Europe. I grew up in England and in
New York, and I suppose the main character is also a survivor of a destroyed

30:20.820 --> 30:33.600
people. So it's sort of allegorical, I suppose. This has happened before in
science fiction in a book called The Falling Torch by Aldous Budras, which is a

30:33.600 --> 30:50.780
thinly disguised story about a Lithuanian exile going back to lead a revolt
against his people, the oppressors. Budras is an exile also from Soviet

30:50.780 --> 31:04.320
-dominated Lithuania. I suppose you could say that the Omega Point dealt with
themes of this kind. I see it as the ghosts of the Hitlerian war walking through

31:05.800 --> 31:17.640
a metaphysical space opera. And in the revenge theme, I suppose, there is a kind
of strength. The book went into seven, eight foreign editions and did quite well

31:17.640 --> 31:30.840
in its original paperback. But I think that when I finally produce the, when the
final three volumes are produced as one book by my publishers, it will be

31:30.840 --> 31:44.440
considerably improved. But I think it will have the same colorful space opera
kind of background. It'll never be better than a certain kind of genre science

31:44.440 --> 31:52.140
fiction. I don't mind that kind of science fiction, but I wish it were better
done than it has been in the past.

31:55.140 --> 32:06.380
It's going to be republished. It's going to be in an improved version. Well, in
effect, the three volumes, Ashes of the Star, The Omega Point, and I think the

32:06.380 --> 32:17.400
third part will be called Mirror of Mind, although that's not quite certain yet.
All three volumes will have been rewritten from scratch, in effect, to produce

32:17.400 --> 32:32.040
the kind of overall intention that I have for the books. They're really one
book. That's what they are. Why do you choose to rewrite old works instead of

32:32.040 --> 32:40.960
just laying them aside and going on to something else? Well, this is only going
to happen. This is only going to happen twice. The middle Omega book I rewrote,

32:41.080 --> 32:53.060
but that's because there is a larger work to which it belongs. It's a question
of making the work even throughout as to the quality of writing. I think that

32:53.060 --> 33:04.920
although the original Omega Point had a certain kind of energy, it was a very
young book and I don't think it did as well as it should have for that theme.

33:06.740 --> 33:17.540
It's unfinished business. That's really what it is. The same thing with Starweb,
which is the first of three volumes, so I can't just leave the first volume as

33:17.540 --> 33:29.940
it is and do the other two volumes. The first one would stick out as a sore
thumb. In time, these six books, I suppose, will be out as two books, each one

33:29.940 --> 33:38.800
in three parts, but they are essentially one work, so you have two books total.
So it's a question of finishing up old business. I'm not rewriting old books for

33:38.800 --> 33:48.720
the sake of rewriting old books, and I'll probably never do this again. The
trick is to write it as well as you deserve the first time, and I think I've

33:48.720 --> 33:58.480
done that with other works. I'll never rewrite the stories in my story
collection, for example, or rewrite Macro Life. They don't need that.

34:02.580 --> 34:13.540
A catchy thing about the Omega Point and the sequel Ashes and Stars is that you
have all sorts of quotes interspersed among the chapters. Do you keep a notebook

34:13.540 --> 34:26.200
of quotes? Do you purposely look for them? How do you remember them all? Well, I
do have a notebook in which I write down things that strike me, and they started

34:26.200 --> 34:41.320
out primarily as springboards of theme and action for various parts of the Omega
trilogy, and after a while I said, well, why not put them in anyway, and the

34:41.320 --> 34:49.840
response I've had, I probably should leave them in, although I think that in the
one volume edition they'll be set in very small type at the beginnings of each

34:49.840 --> 35:01.100
chapter. I've been of two minds over this, whether to leave it out or not. I
don't know what they add to the overall book, but perhaps they add a kind of

35:01.100 --> 35:04.120
thoughtfulness that would be otherwise missing.

35:06.860 --> 35:18.980
As an aside, I definitely agree, they do. I was very happy to hear that from
somebody else besides myself. Okay, Star Web was one of the few pretty good

35:18.980 --> 35:31.460
laser books. How did you get convinced to write a laser book? Well, as with many
other writers who came to prominence in the 70s, Roger Rowe had contacted at

35:31.460 --> 35:44.120
least 100 writers. Other writers who had written quite a few stories for Roger
were Barry Maltzberg, Gene Wolfe, Philip Farmer, almost anyone you can think of.

35:44.260 --> 35:56.940
Just go look in your contento bibliography and you'll see how many writers wrote
stories for Roger's endless pit of demands. I was asked to write one of the

35:56.940 --> 36:09.580
laser books and I didn't concoct the laser book. I simply submitted a book that
I was planning to write anyway and it went over. I regret that I had to write it

36:09.580 --> 36:24.620
in such a short period of time which is why I have rewritten it. But the proof
of perhaps the book's quality is that it has gone from a laser paperback to

36:24.620 --> 36:33.160
volume one of a double-day trilogy in hardcover. Very few books make the passage
from paperback into hardcover. It goes the other way usually.

36:36.540 --> 36:47.580
You had at least one other association with Roger Elwood. I think I wrote about
12 stories for him all total. They were stories that I was writing anyway and he

36:47.580 --> 37:02.400
simply said okay I'll commission it and as soon as the story was ready it turns
out that he bought it. Roger Elwood is often reviled now for various reasons. Do

37:02.400 --> 37:15.300
you think that he had an overall positive effect on the field? Well he Roger the
problem of Roger Elwood goes two ways. One science fiction writers are generally

37:15.300 --> 37:16.260
irreligious.

37:20.540 --> 37:36.660
They want to see what they write. published. Roger was a religious person I
think he's a Baptist who had some very strong ideas as to what science fiction

37:36.660 --> 37:47.400
should be although if you look at what he bought he bought about the same kind
of thing that almost anybody else would buy. The positive effect is he gave a

37:47.400 --> 38:01.580
lot of life and a lot of living to many many writers who would not have been
able to write and publish as much. The problem is that he brought out the worst

38:01.580 --> 38:14.540
in many writers. He had such a large need for fiction that he bought just about
everything that most writers could produce. even works even works that he would

38:14.540 --> 38:25.140
reject. Later when an opportunity would present itself he would buy the work. He
would get back to you and say you know that story I rejected six months ago I

38:25.140 --> 38:36.900
think I have a place where I could use it. And then he would buy it. The
difficulty with this is that no matter what editor was doing what Roger did they

38:36.900 --> 38:46.380
would have this problem. Namely that there is a limited amount of first rate
material. So if you had certain numbers of pages to fill he had about 70

38:46.380 --> 38:58.020
anthologies to his credit I think. With various magazine writing stints, editing
stints, no matter who was doing what Roger did they would have to fill those

38:58.020 --> 39:07.320
pages up especially if they'd signed contracts. So eventually the criterion
became that of minimal professionalism. If something was professional and

39:07.320 --> 39:19.160
readable and if it fit the particular anthology in it went. And Roger ran up
against the difficulty of getting work at a high level in a short period of

39:19.160 --> 39:31.880
time. It just can't be done. So it's partially his fault that he provided the
opportunity but I think it's also the fault of the field that the level of

39:31.880 --> 39:44.300
writing and ambition was so low that we were producing at this level because
most of the stories he bought were not concocted for him. They were stories that

39:44.300 --> 39:56.940
these writers were writing or had in their trunks. Many writers sold him all
their trunks of material that had not been published elsewhere. Is that clear

39:56.940 --> 40:07.900
enough on that? That's great. That's what I wanted to know. I'll ask one more
question then we'll flip our tape. Your collection the most... Before we just go

40:07.900 --> 40:19.660
on I'd like to say that there are half a dozen Elwood anthologies that are
outstanding and that will probably deserve to remain in print. The Continuum

40:19.660 --> 40:26.180
series of four books Epoch Showcase just to name the best.

